<div class="text-block row">
	<div class="large-8 columns large-offset-2">
		<h4>Results: Support for Option A</h4>
		<p>In general, the users who preferred Option A thought it looked better aesthetically, thought that it avoided Option B's confusing juxtaposition of similar shapes, and did a good job of integrating the music and audio functionalities.</p>
		<h5>Looked cleaner.</h5>
		<blockquote>"Makes the buttons look like they're taking up less space – like an optical illusion."</blockquote>
		<h5>Easier to differentiate play/pause from the 'next' button.</h5>
		<blockquote>"Can see what the buttons mean in a snap – have to think about it for option B."</blockquote>
		<blockquote>"[In Option B] the play button and the next button look almost the same next to each other...the triangles get confusing."</blockquote>
		<h5>Grouping the phone features together make sense.</h5>
		<blockquote>"Makes sense that the two call buttons are grouped together."</blockquote>
		<blockquote>"[Option B] disassociates play and pause from a call feature. It looks only music related."</blockquote>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="text-block row">
	<div class="large-8 columns large-offset-2">
		<h4>A hiccup: Muting</h4>
		<p>I found that nobody felt confident about how to mute themselves on a call, and did not know how to even activate mute on the current JAMBOX.</p>
		<p>When guessing how to mute, users tried the play/pause button, the phone button, as well as the minus button. However, when told how the mute actually worked (it was the pause button), they were able to rationalize it.</p>
		<blockquote>It's like pausing a conversation instead of pausing music.</blockquote>
		<blockquote>It's like pausing my sound.</blockquote>
		<blockquote>I might think it was the phone button, but then I'd be nervous that it would end a call.</blockquote>
	</div>
</div>

